# Brief: <part number> datasheet

A short statement of what the drafter should produce: a customer-facing
datasheet (`datasheet.tex`) compiling under XeLaTeX, following the shipped
template's layout conventions (two-column first page, fresh-page major
sections, consistent rev/footer), scoring against the 9-dimension /44 rubric
(advance ≥39 — customer-facing tier), and passing the mandatory audit (spec
source-of-truth cross-check + pin-map/bus-width integrity + revision-history
gate + family coherence).

**Put the spec bundle in `<thread>/refs/` before drafting.** Every numeric
claim must trace to an authoritative source — design-model export, quant/config
export, RTL parameter export, foundry quote, package drawing. Text-readable
exports (`.md` / `.txt` / `.json`) are read as authoritative; the spec bundle
outranks numbers stated in this brief.

## Part identity

What the part is, the base die it is built on, and (for multi-SKU families)
which sibling SKUs exist and what differentiates them. Name the shared-die
spec blocks explicitly (process, die, package, abs-max, DC) — the auditor
checks them byte-for-byte against sibling sheets.

## Key features / applications

The first-page bullets (one line each). Numbers quoted here must match the
spec tables — the canary's performance-header-vs-body drift is a dim 2 finding.

## Interfaces and pinout

The package, pin count, and interface set. The drafter emits the pinout table
between `% anvil-pinmap-begin` / `% anvil-pinmap-end` markers so the pin-map
checker can assert every pin is assigned exactly once.

## Registers / fields with claimed ranges

Any N-bit field whose value range the sheet will claim (index buses, register
fields). The drafter emits an `% anvil-bus: name=<field> width=<W> max=<M>`
marker per claim so the bus-width checker can verify 2^W covers it.

## Performance posture

Which network/configuration and input size the performance tables quote, at
which operating point, and the provenance of each number (simulated /
estimated / measured). On a `status: preliminary` sheet every pre-silicon
value carries a label (`\est{}`, `\simval{}`, or a Notes-column entry).
